"Hansen J., Sato M., Kharecha P., Von Schuckmann K.","Earth's energy imbalance and implications",2011,"Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics","11","24",,"13421","13449",,,10.5194/acp-11-13421-2011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84555194782&partnerID=40&md5=307c8368b02a07b9d568c2ac960c88c3","NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States; Columbia University Earth Institute, New York, NY 10027, United States; Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, LOCEAN Paris, Hosted by Ifremer, Brest, France","Hansen, J., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Columbia University Earth Institute, New York, NY 10027, United States; Sato, M., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Columbia University Earth Institute, New York, NY 10027, United States; Kharecha, P., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Columbia University Earth Institute, New York, NY 10027, United States; Von Schuckmann, K., Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique, LOCEAN Paris, Hosted by Ifremer, Brest, France","Improving observations of ocean heat content show that Earth is absorbing more energy from the Sun than it is radiating to space as heat, even during the recent solar minimum. The inferred planetary energy imbalance, 0.58 ± 0.15 W mg -2 during the 6-yr period 2005-2010, confirms the dominant role of the human-made greenhouse effect in driving global climate change. Observed surface temperature change and ocean heat gain together constrain the net climate forcing and ocean mixing rates. We conclude that most climate models mix heat too efficiently into the deep ocean and as a result underestimate the negative forcing by human-made aerosols. Aerosol climate forcing today is inferred to be g -1.6 ± 0.3 W mg -2, implying substantial aerosol indirect climate forcing via cloud changes. Continued failure to quantify the specific origins of this large forcing is untenable, as knowledge of changing aerosol effects is needed to understand future climate change. We conclude that recent slowdown of ocean heat uptake was caused by a delayed rebound effect from Mount Pinatubo aerosols and a deep prolonged solar minimum. Observed sea level rise during the Argo float era is readily accounted for by ice melt and ocean thermal expansion, but the ascendency of ice melt leads us to anticipate acceleration of the rate of sea level rise this decade. © Author(s) 2011. CC Attribution 3.0 License.",,"aerosol; air-sea interaction; climate forcing; climate modeling; energy balance; greenhouse effect; heat flow; heat source; radiation balance; sea level change; solar radiation; surface temperature; thermal expansion; Central Luzon; Luzon; Mount Pinatubo; Philippines; Zambales; Pinatubo",,,,,,"Barker, P.M., Dunn, J.R., Domingues, C.M., Wijffels, S.E., Pressure sensor drifts in Argo and their impacts (2011) J. Atmos. Oceanic Tech., , in press, doi:10.1175/2011JTECHO831; Barnett, T.P., Pierce, D.W., AchutaRao, K.M., Gleckler, P.J., Santer, B.D., Gregory, J.M., Washington, W.M., Ocean science: Penetration of human-induced warming into the world's oceans (2005) Science, 309 (5732), pp. 284-287. , DOI 10.1126/science.1112418; Beltrami, H., Climate from borehole data: Energy fluxes and temperatures since 1500 (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29, p. 2111. , doi:10.1029/2002GL015702; Beltrami, H., Smerdon, J.E., Pollack, H.N., Huang, S., Continental heat gain in the global climate system (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29, p. 1167. , doi:10.1029/2001GL014310; Bleck, R., An oceanic general circulation model framed in hybrid isopycnic-Cartesian coordinates (2002) Ocean Modelling, 4 (1), pp. 55-88. , DOI 10.1016/S1463-5003(01)00012-9, PII S1463500301000129; Bromwich, D.H., Nicolas, J.P., Ice-sheet uncertainty (2010) Nat. Geosci., 3, pp. 596-597; Bryan, K., A numerical model for the study of the circulation of the world ocean (1969) J. Comp. Phys.